description.value: An animal-shaped spout, broken from a terracotta vessel, apparently the head of a harnessed horse, but very stylized, with a long tubular muzzle acting as a spout: possibly a cockerel's head. The basic head was wheel-thrown, with a domed end; the muzzle was hand-modelled and applied. The eyes are rounded knobs of clay added to the head, the eyeballs defined by the use of a tubular tool; the small ears were pinched-out. The crossover harness was then applied. Red Nile silt with a grey core and some white inclusions, the outside covered overall with a cream-coloured slip; red-brown fired-on ceramic colours on the harness, eyes and ears.

description.value: 17 small pottery sherds from two black ware bowls, of an open form with a flat base. The deoxidised fabric is very fine and contains no organic temper; lots of large sand particles, some scattered tiny black and grey stones, and tiny pieces of mica. It is decorated on the exterior with impressed wedge-shaped stamps in geometric cross-hatched patterns. These are filled with white and red pigment. The rim in burnished, and the cross-hatched squares are separated by lines of burnishing. A hole is visible in one sherd, which may suggest it was used for suspension or broken and then repaired. Some burnishing on interior.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta stamp fragment. A fragment of a large circular bread-stamp (?) with an applied oval-sectioned, but much damaged, grip on the centre back. The pattern is largely incuse, but with some relief detail: within an inward facing egg-and-dart border is a frontal bull’s head, with ribbons and tassels depending on each side. The ribbon on the proper right side of the stamp supports a pendent shrine-shaped amulet with two uraeus cornices: part of the amulet is interrupted by an ovolo.  Face covered with a good quality red slip, with runs on the back. Pressed over a plaster form, with traces of this plaster in the mould. Red-brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and few white grits.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta circular stamp. A circular bread-stamp (?), with an applied circular grip on the centre back. It has an incuse pattern: within a border of truncated segmented panels each containing a circular depression, a victorious cockerel walks to left (in the impression), with a palm branch rising from his back; in front of the bird is a series of small circular depressions of varying sizes. Pressed over a modelled form; the back, with the handle, was subsequently turned on a wheel. Orange-brown Nile silt with a surface fired red-brown, abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.
